summary: Blood was trickling down Sansa's brow from a deep gash on her scalp. "They . . . they were throwing things . . . rocks and...
body:
Blood was trickling down Sansa’s brow from a deep gash on her scalp. “They … they were throwing things … rocks and filth, eggs … I tried to tell them, I had no bread to give them. A man tried to pull me from the saddle. The Hound killed him, I think … his arm …” Her eyes widened and she put a hand over her mouth. “He cut off his arm.”

Sansa was caught in the middle of a riot, assaulted and was likely about to be raped like Lollys Stokeworth was and her only response was ‘I have no bread to give you.’ The bravery first of all (I would be screaming and crying incoherently), the strength, the way she sees (most of) them as starving people. How anyone could still claim Sansa was too classist to recognise that peasants are humans I don’t know. 

Oh and let’s add this to Sansa’s many traumas.

summary: Me he dado cuenta de que el moño de Sansa parece  una serpiente ouroboros. Definición de la serpiente ouroboros: Una de las...
caption:
Me he dado cuenta de que el moño de Sansa parece  una serpiente ouroboros.

Definición de la serpiente ouroboros:

Una de las apariciones más impactantes de las serpientes en la cultura antigua es el Ouroboros, la serpiente dragon que se muerde la cola, que se devora a sí misma, que se nutre de sí misma. Es principio y fin, generadora de vida y muerte. El Ouroboros reúne, así, los contenidos de varios símbolos en uno: la serpiente, las alas, la renovación, el círculo.

El Ouróboros es un símbolo que muestra a un animal serpentiforme, engullendo su propia cola, conformando con su cuerpo una forma circular o de “8”.  

El Ouroboros, representado por una serpiente alada con rasgos de dragón devorando su cola, reúne, en un sentido esotérico, los contenidos de varios símbolos en uno: la serpiente, el dragón, las alas, la renovación, el círculo.

La serpiente representa la sabiduría ancestral, el mito primigenio del mundo subterráneo y la fuerza primitiva de la vida; es signo del tiempo que se reproduce eternamente, pues al cambiar de piel se rejuvenece, y al doblarse sobre sí misma evoca la curva del cielo, imagen esotérica del universo, así como su mito encarna la sublimación de lo material; el dragón es la personificación reptiliana del poder primordial, guardián vinculado al inframundo y al conocimiento de los oráculos; el círculo es la idea sintética de la perfección.

Sabemos que la serpiente al cambiar de piel se rejuvenece constantemente, es el símbolo más significativo y complejo de todos los símbolos animales, y tal vez el más antiguo: combina lo masculino y lo femenino, es la fuerza primitiva de la vida, emblema de la divinidad creadora misma.

Todo esto encaja a la perfección con Sansa, con Jon y con los Stark en general y como bien cantaba la pobre Shireen “Los pajaros tienen escamas y los peces alas, lo se lo se”

summary: Sansa was actually the one that got me into the show. I’ve seen edits of Margery and D before that and it looked interesting but...
question: Sansa was actually the one that got me into the show. I’ve seen edits of Margery and D before that and it looked interesting but Sansa was the one that made me commit. I saw a post explaining her political prowess during the scene with Joffrey before the battle at Blackwater. When I saw that post, I was a goner. She reminded me of myself. Ofc my situation isn’t as dire but she reminds me of ppl that makes best of their situation and overcomes their adversaries without losing their kindness
answer:
I really hope your situation isn’t as dire :s

And exactly. I admired Sansa so much during her entire arc in KL, because even though it didn’t look like it, she was fighting back. Her passiveness hid her resistance and she went under everyone’s radars, desperately learning from all the monsters constantly surrounding her while never letting their teachings turn her into another Cersei or Littlefinger. She got smarter, she survived, and she did it without ever losing her compassion in the process.

That’s why I can’t understand the reasoning of those who believe that she’ll die in S8. Sansa Stark is a survivor, that’s literally her entire arc, and if there’s one person who’ll make it through the Long Night, it’s her.

summary: Sansans are so full of bullshit
body:
Sansans are so full of bullshit

They say they only want the ship to happen when Sansa is an adult, yet constantly write fic nd draw artwork of child!Sansa and Adult!Sandor.

Besides, they go on about “their passionate reunion” and fantasize about kissing scenes and graphic sex scenes in TWOW/ADOS, even though Sansa would be, at most, 15- more likely 14, during ADOS. They don’t talk about the possibility of it being merely confirmed in an epilogue or something like that, which to me shows that that was always an excuse.

(This goes for Sanrion and Petyr x Sansa)

@sayruq @cleverjonquil

summary: Jon and Sansa’s close sibling relationship.
body:
Jon and Sansa’s close sibling relationship.

Sansa “I’ve had a lot of time to think about how awful I was to you”

…

Jon “You were occasionally awful.”

“I’m sure I can’t have been much fun always skulking in the corner watching the rest of you play. “

About the only thing the show runners decided was important enough to tell us about Jon and Sansa’s sibling relationship.


She was awful to him and they didn’t play together.
